A data source in Terraform is used to fetch information about existing infrastructure that is not managed by the current Terraform configuration so it can be referenced in Terraform configuration without creating or managing that resource.It allows Terraform to read attributes such as AMI IDs, VPC details, or subnet information and use them while creating new resources. Unlike resources, data sources do not create or manage infrastructure; they only retrieve information.
          data "aws_ami" "latest_amazon_linux" {
            most_recent = true
          
            owners = ["amazon"]
          
            filter {
              name   = "name"
              values = ["amzn2-ami-hvm-*"]
            }
          }
          
          resource "aws_instance" "web" {
            ami           = data.aws_ami.latest_amazon_linux.id
            instance_type = "t2.micro"
          }
Locals in Terraform are used to define reusable values or expressions within a configuration. They help avoid repeating the same values multiple times and improve code readability and maintainability. Locals are evaluated within the module and can be referenced using the local keyword.
        locals {
          project       = "08-input-vars-locals-outputs"
          project_owner = "terraform-course"
          cost_center   = "1234"
          managed_by    = "Terraform"
        }
        locals {
          common_tags = {
            project       = local.project
            project_owner = local.project_owner
            cost_center   = local.cost_center
            managed_by    = local.managed_by
          }
        }
      resource "aws_instance" "compute" {
      ami           = data.aws_ami.ubuntu.id
      instance_type = var.ec2_instance_type
    
      root_block_device {
        delete_on_termination = true
        volume_size           = var.ec2_volume_config.size
        volume_type           = var.ec2_volume_config.type
      }
    
      tags = merge(local.common_tags, var.additional_tags)
    }
In Terraform, lists and maps are collection data types used to store multiple values. A list is an ordered sequence of elements of the same type, while a map stores key-value pairs.
